---
import CaseStudy from '@/layouts/CaseStudy.astro';

// NOTE: No README for this one, so the copy below is inferred from the resume
// line ("Compendium of material written in LaTeX covering topics from Numerical
// Linear Algebra to Real Analysis") plus the fact that it's published to GitHub
// Pages. Swap in the real chapter list and toolchain when you have a minute.
---

<CaseStudy
	title="Math-o-nomicon — case study"
	description="A typeset compendium of graduate mathematics, from numerical linear algebra through real analysis, published as a browsable notebook."
	eyebrow="Ongoing — since 2024"
	heading="Math-o-nomicon"
	status="Living document"
	lede="Lecture notes are disposable by design. This is the attempt to turn four years of them into one typeset reference that's actually worth returning to."
	meta={[
		{ label: 'Stack', value: 'LaTeX · TikZ · GitHub Pages' },
		{ label: 'Type', value: 'Reference compendium' },
		{ label: 'Read', value: 'arenvista.github.io/notebook', href: 'https://arenvista.github.io/notebook/' }
	]}
>
	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>Why</h2>
		<p>
			Notes taken during a lecture are optimised for keeping up, not for being read later.
			They fragment across courses, lose their cross-references, and go stale the moment the
			semester ends — which is exactly when you start needing them, whether that's for a
			qualifying exam or for explaining a proof to someone at a tutoring desk.
		</p>
		<p>
			The Math-o-nomicon rewrites them as one document with a single voice, a single set of
			conventions, and links that hold across chapters.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>What's in it</h2>
		<p>
			The spine runs from numerical linear algebra through analysis, with the numerical
			material carrying most of the weight so far:
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Orthogonal matrices, QR factorization, and least squares.</li>
			<li>Conditioning and numerical stability — where the error actually comes from.</li>
			<li>The SVD, Eckart–Young, and the pseudoinverse.</li>
			<li>The spectral theorem, Schur factorization, and iterative eigenvalue methods.</li>
			<li>Newton's method and Gauss–Newton, tied back to the linear machinery underneath.</li>
			<li>Real analysis, as the foundation the numerical chapters keep quietly borrowing from.</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>The conventions</h2>
		<p>
			Consistency is the whole feature. Definitions, theorems, proofs, and asides each get a
			fixed treatment, so a reader learns the visual grammar once and never has to decode it
			again. Diagrams are drawn in TikZ rather than pasted as images, which keeps them
			editable and keeps the type matching the body text.
		</p>
		<p>
			Every chapter closes by pointing forward: the section on QR says what it's setting up
			for least squares, and the section on Gauss–Newton says which earlier chapter it's
			standing on. A theorem in isolation is trivia — the throughline is what makes it a book.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="cs__section">
		<h2>What I took away</h2>
		<p>
			Writing something down for a stranger is a different operation from writing it down for
			yourself, and it surfaces every place you were relying on a gap you'd stopped noticing.
			More than one chapter got rewritten because typesetting the proof made it obvious I
			couldn't actually justify a step I'd been waving through for two years.
		</p>
	</section>
</CaseStudy>
